  39 try:
  40     from tempfile import _infer_return_type
  41 except ImportError:
  42 
  43     def _infer_return_type(*args):
  44         _types = set()
  45         for arg in args:
  46             if isinstance(type(arg), six.string_types):
  47                 _types.add(str)
  48             elif isinstance(type(arg), bytes):
  49                 _types.add(bytes)
  50             elif arg:
  51                 _types.add(type(arg))
  52         return _types.pop()
  53 
  54 
  55 def _sanitize_params(prefix, suffix, dir):
  56     """Common parameter processing for most APIs in this module."""
  57     output_type = _infer_return_type(prefix, suffix, dir)
  58     if suffix is None:
  59         suffix = output_type()
  60     if prefix is None:
  61         if output_type is str:
  62             prefix = "tmp"
  63         else:
  64             prefix = os.fsencode("tmp")
  65     if dir is None:
  66         if output_type is str:
  67             dir = gettempdir()
  68         else:
  69             dir = fs_encode(gettempdir())
  70     return prefix, suffix, dir, output_type

  73 class _TemporaryFileCloser:
  74     """A separate object allowing proper closing of a temporary file's
  75     underlying file object, without adding a __del__ method to the
  76     temporary file."""
  77 
  78     file = None  # Set here since __del__ checks it
  79     close_called = False
  80 
  81     def __init__(self, file, name, delete=True):
  82         self.file = file
  83         self.name = name
  84         self.delete = delete
  85 
  86     # NT provides delete-on-close as a primitive, so we don't need
  87     # the wrapper to do anything special.  We still use it so that
  88     # file.name is useful (i.e. not "(fdopen)") with NamedTemporaryFile.
  89     if os.name != "nt":
  90 
  91         # Cache the unlinker so we don't get spurious errors at
  92         # shutdown when the module-level "os" is None'd out.  Note
  93         # that this must be referenced as self.unlink, because the
  94         # name TemporaryFileWrapper may also get None'd out before
  95         # __del__ is called.
  96 
  97         def close(self, unlink=os.unlink):
  98             if not self.close_called and self.file is not None:
  99                 self.close_called = True
 100                 try:
 101                     self.file.close()
 102                 finally:
 103                     if self.delete:
 104                         unlink(self.name)
 105 
 106         # Need to ensure the file is deleted on __del__
 107 
 108         def __del__(self):
 109             self.close()
 110 
 111     else:
 112 
 113         def close(self):
 114             if not self.close_called:
 115                 self.close_called = True
 116                 self.file.close()

 119 class _TemporaryFileWrapper:
 120     """Temporary file wrapper
 121     This class provides a wrapper around files opened for
 122     temporary use.  In particular, it seeks to automatically
 123     remove the file when it is no longer needed.
 124     """
 125 
 126     def __init__(self, file, name, delete=True):
 127         self.file = file
 128         self.name = name
 129         self.delete = delete
 130         self._closer = _TemporaryFileCloser(file, name, delete)
 131 
 132     def __getattr__(self, name):
 133         # Attribute lookups are delegated to the underlying file
 134         # and cached for non-numeric results
 135         # (i.e. methods are cached, closed and friends are not)
 136         file = self.__dict__["file"]
 137         a = getattr(file, name)
 138         if hasattr(a, "__call__"):
 139             func = a
 140 
 141             @functools.wraps(func)
 142             def func_wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
 143                 return func(*args, **kwargs)
 144 
 145             # Avoid closing the file as long as the wrapper is alive,
 146             # see issue #18879.
 147             func_wrapper._closer = self._closer
 148             a = func_wrapper
 149         if not isinstance(a, int):
 150             setattr(self, name, a)
 151         return a
 152 
 153     # The underlying __enter__ method returns the wrong object
 154     # (self.file) so override it to return the wrapper
 155 
 156     def __enter__(self):
 157         self.file.__enter__()
 158         return self
 159 
 160     # Need to trap __exit__ as well to ensure the file gets
 161     # deleted when used in a with statement
 162 
 163     def __exit__(self, exc, value, tb):
 164         result = self.file.__exit__(exc, value, tb)
 165         self.close()
 166         return result
 167 
 168     def close(self):
 169         """
 170         Close the temporary file, possibly deleting it.
 171         """
 172         self._closer.close()
 173 
 174     # iter() doesn't use __getattr__ to find the __iter__ method
 175 
 176     def __iter__(self):
 177         # Don't return iter(self.file), but yield from it to avoid closing
 178         # file as long as it's being used as iterator (see issue #23700).  We
 179         # can't use 'yield from' here because iter(file) returns the file
 180         # object itself, which has a close method, and thus the file would get
 181         # closed when the generator is finalized, due to PEP380 semantics.
 182         for line in self.file:
 183             yield line
 184

 186 def NamedTemporaryFile(
 187     mode="w+b",
 188     buffering=-1,
 189     encoding=None,
 190     newline=None,
 191     suffix=None,
 192     prefix=None,
 193     dir=None,
 194     delete=True,
 195     wrapper_class_override=None,
 196 ):
 197     """Create and return a temporary file.
 198     Arguments:
 199     'prefix', 'suffix', 'dir' -- as for mkstemp.
 200     'mode' -- the mode argument to io.open (default "w+b").
 201     'buffering' -- the buffer size argument to io.open (default -1).
 202     'encoding' -- the encoding argument to io.open (default None)
 203     'newline' -- the newline argument to io.open (default None)
 204     'delete' -- whether the file is deleted on close (default True).
 205     The file is created as mkstemp() would do it.
 206     Returns an object with a file-like interface; the name of the file
 207     is accessible as its 'name' attribute.  The file will be automatically
 208     deleted when it is closed unless the 'delete' argument is set to False.
 209     """
 210     prefix, suffix, dir, output_type = _sanitize_params(prefix, suffix, dir)
 211     flags = _bin_openflags
 212     # Setting O_TEMPORARY in the flags causes the OS to delete
 213     # the file when it is closed.  This is only supported by Windows.
 214     if not wrapper_class_override:
 215         wrapper_class_override = _TemporaryFileWrapper
 216     if os.name == "nt" and delete:
 217         flags |= os.O_TEMPORARY
 218     if sys.version_info < (3, 5):
 219         (fd, name) = _mkstemp_inner(dir, prefix, suffix, flags)
 220     else:
 221         (fd, name) = _mkstemp_inner(dir, prefix, suffix, flags, output_type)
 222     try:
 223         file = io.open(fd, mode, buffering=buffering, newline=newline, encoding=encoding)
 224         if wrapper_class_override is not None:
 225             return type(str("_TempFileWrapper"), (wrapper_class_override, object), {})(
 226                 file, name, delete
 227             )
 228         else:
 229             return _TemporaryFileWrapper(file, name, delete)
 230 
 231     except BaseException:
 232         os.unlink(name)
 233         os.close(fd)
 234         raise
